Annual Grammy Awards|1985]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Music Film|Best Video Album]]\n|''[[Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This) (album)#Sweet Dreams: The Video Album|Eurythmics Sweet Dreams: The Video Album]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[28th Annual Grammy Awards|1986]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocals|Best R&B Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n|\"[[Sisters Are Doin' It for Themselves]]\" <small>(with [[Aretha Franklin]])</small>\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Grammy Award for Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal|Best Rock Performance by a Duo or Group with Vocal]]\n|\"[[Would I Lie to You? (Eurythmics song)|Would I Lie to You?]]\"\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| [[29th Annual Grammy Awards|1987]]\n|\"[[Missionary Man (Eurythmics song)|Missionary Man]]\"\n|{{won}}\n|-\n| [[32nd Annual Grammy Awards|1990]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Grammy Award for Best Music Film|Best Music Video \u2013 Long Form]]\n|[[Savage (video)|''Savage'']]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| [[33rd Annual Grammy Awards|1991]]\n|''[[We Two Are One Too]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"| [[35th Annual Grammy Awards|1993]]\n|rowspan=\"3\"|''[[Diva (Annie Lennox album)|Diva]]''\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Grammy Award for Album of the Year|Album of the Year]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Pop Vocal Performance, Femal]]''[[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|e]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[38th Annual Grammy Awards|1996]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Female Pop Vocal Performance|Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]]\n|\"[[No More 'I Love You's]]\"\n|{{won}}\n|-\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Album]]\n|''[[Medusa (Annie Lennox album)|Medusa]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| [[46th Annual Grammy Awards|2004]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Vocal Albu]]<nowiki/>m\n|[[Bare (Annie Lennox album)|''Bare'']]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n| [[47th Annual Grammy Awards|2005]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media|Best Song Written for a Motion Picture, Television or Other Visual Media]]\n|\"[[Into the West (song)|Into the West (From ''The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King'')]]\"\n|{{won}}\n|-\n| [[57th Annual Grammy Awards|2015]]\n|[[Grammy Award for Best Traditional Pop Vocal Album|Best Traditional Pop Vocal Album]]\n|''[[Nostalgia (Annie Lennox album)|Nostalgia]]''\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|}\n\n===MTV Video Music Awards===\n{{award table}}\n|-\n| [[1989 MTV Video Music Awards|1989]]\n| \"[[Put a Little Love in Your Heart]]\"\n| [[MTV Video Music Award for Best Video from a Film|Best Video from a Film]]\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\"| [[1992 MTV Video Music Awards|1992]]\n| rowspan=\"2\"|\"[[Why (Annie Lennox song)|Why]]\"\n| [[MTV Video Music Award \u2013 Viewer's Choice|Viewer's Choice]]\n|{{nom}}\n|-\n|rowspan=3|[[MTV Video Music Award for Best Female Video|Best Female Video]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n| [[1993 MTV Video Music Awards|1993]]\n| \"[[Walking on Broken Glass]]\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[1996 MTV Video Music Awards|1996]]\n| \"[[No More 'I Love You's]]\"\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n; [[American Music Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annielennox.com |title=American Music Awards listed on official website |publisher=Annielennox.com |date=15 October 2010 |accessdate=27 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101206180756/http://www.annielennox.com/| archivedate= 6 December 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n*[[American Music Awards of 2008|2008]] \u2013 AMA Award of Merit for her work and her humanitarian efforts\n\n; [[Ivor Novello Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annielennox.com |title=Ivor Novello Awards listed on official website |publisher=Annielennox.com |date=15 October 2010 |accessdate=27 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101206180756/http://www.annielennox.com/| archivedate= 6 December 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n*1984 \u2013 Songwriter of the Year for Lennox and Dave Stewart\n*1987 \u2013 Songwriter of the Year for Lennox and Dave Stewart\n*1987 \u2013 Best contemporary song (\"Its Alright, (Baby's Coming Back)\")\n*1993 \u2013 Best Song (\"Why\")\n\n; [[Honorary degrees]] and awards<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annielennox.com |title=Honorary degrees/ Awards listed on official website |publisher=Annielennox.com |date=15 October 2010 |accessdate=27 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101206180756/http://www.annielennox.com/| archivedate= 6 December 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n*1986 \u2013 Associate \u2013 [[Royal Academy of Music]] London\n*1997 \u2013 Fellowship \u2013 [[Royal Academy of Music]] London\n*2006 \u2013 Honorary Doctor of Music \u2013 The [[Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama]]\n*2006 \u2013 Fellowship \u2013 [[Edinburgh College of Art]]\n*2009 \u2013 Honorary Doctorate at the [[University of Edinburgh]] (awarded 20 October 2009), in recognition of her work in the field of HIV/AIDS, and her success as a recording artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ed.ac.uk/news/all-news/lennox-201009 |title=Annie Lennox receives honorary degree &#124; News and events |publisher=Ed.ac.uk |date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref>\n*2011 \u2013 Honoured by the University for her International Humanitarian Efforts \u2013 [[Glasgow Caledonian University]]  \n*2012 \u2013 Honorary Degree  \u2013 [[Open University]] of Scotland\n*2013 \u2013 Honorary Degree \u2013 [[Williams College]] \n*2013 \u2013 Honorary Doctorate in Music \u2013 [[Berklee College of Music]] \n*2013 \u2013 Honorary Degree \u2013 [[University of Essex]]\n\n; Other awards/titles/ambassadorships<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annielennox.com |title=Other awards/titles/ambassadorships listed on official website |publisher=Annielennox.com |date=15 October 2010 |accessdate=27 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101206180756/http://www.annielennox.com/ |archivedate=6 December 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*2002 \u2013 [[Billboard Century Award]] by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard'']]\n*2008 \u2013 OUT magazine honoured Lennox for her work in the HIV and AIDS field. The top 100 most influential people in Gay Culture.\n*2008 \u2013 The British Red Cross Services to Humanity Award\n*2008 \u2013 Glamour Magazine's Inspirational Woman of the Year Award\n*2008 \u2013 Honoured at the 2008 Youth AIDS Gala, for her contribution in helping the fight against HIV and AIDS\n*2008 \u2013 The German Sustainability \"special achievement\" award for her commitment in the fight against HIV and AIDS\n*2008 \u2013 [[Webby Award]] for official website www.annielennox.com<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Iuj6Lt1lbLc |title=Lennox's acceptance speech video on Youtube |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref>\n*2009 \u2013 [[Save the Children]] \"Amigo de los Ni\u00f1os\" Award\n*2009 \u2013 Awarded the \"[[Freedom of the City of London]]\" by the British Red Cross for services to humanity in the field of HIV and AIDS\n*2009 \u2013 Nobel Peace Laureates for services to humanity\n*2010 \u2013 Patron of the [[Elton John AIDS Foundation]]\n*2010 \u2013 Special Envoy for HIV/AIDS in Scotland\n*2010 \u2013 Ambassador for HIV/AIDS in London\n*2010 \u2013 [[UNAIDS]] Goodwill Ambassador\n*2010 \u2013 [[Barclays]] Women of the Year Award\n*2010 \u2013 International Service Award for Global Defence of Human Rights<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internationalservice.org.uk/what_we_do/development_awareness/human_rights_awards/2010_awards/annie_lennox.aspx|title=International Service \u2013 annie lennox|publisher=Internationservice.org.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911165632/http://www.internationalservice.org.uk/what_we_do/development_awareness/human_rights_awards/2010_awards/annie_lennox.aspx|archivedate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n*2010 \u2013 [[GQ]] Charity Woman of the Year Award\n*2010 \u2013 Harper's Bazaar Lifetime Achievement Award\n*2010 \u2013 Appointed an [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) for her work fighting AIDS and poverty in Africa\n*2013 \u2013 Music Industry Trust Award (MITS) for her creativity and work that inspires those who work within the music business and millions of others worldwide\n*2016 \u2013 [[Elle Style Awards]] \u2013 Outstanding Achievement Award\n*2016 \u2013 Awarded [[Livingstone Medal]] by [[Royal Scottish Geographical Society]] \n*2016 \u2013 Harper's Bazaar Philanthropy Award\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Annie Lennox}}\n{{Sister project links |commons=Annie Lennox}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.annielennox.com}}\n* {{AllMusic|id=annie-lennox-mn0000585249|name=Annie Lennox}}\n* [https://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n92080019/ Annie Lennox] in libraries ([[WorldCat]] catalogue)\n* {{IMDb name|0005142}}\n\n{{Annie Lennox}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards for Annie Lennox\n| list =\n{{AcademyAwardBestOriginalSong 2001\u20132010}}\n{{Brit British Female}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song}}\n{{Grammy Award for Best Song Written for Visual Media}}\n}}\n{{Eurythmics}}\n{{The Tourists}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Biography |Scotland|Music |United Kingdom | Opera |Film |Africa}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lennox, Annie}}\n[[Category:Annie Lennox| ]]\n[[Category:19 Recordings artists]]\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish singers]]\n[[Category:20th-century women singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Scottish singers]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:Arista Records artists]]\n[[Category:Best Original Song Academy Award-winning songwriters]]\n[[Category:Brit Award winners]]\n[[Category:British female singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:British synth-pop new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:Decca Records artists]]\n[[Category:Eurythmics members]]\n[[Category:Female new wave singers]]\n[[Category:Feminist musicians]]\n[[Category:Freemen of the City of London]]\n[[Category:Grammy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Academy of Music]]\n[[Category:HIV/AIDS activists]]\n[[Category:Ivor Novello Award winners]]\n[[Category:LGBT rights activists from Scotland]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:People educated at Harlaw Academy]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:Scottish activists]]\n[[Category:Scottish agnostics]]\n[[Category:Scottish contraltos]]\n[[Category:Scottish electronic musicians]]\n[[Category:Scottish female singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish feminists]]\n[[Category:Scottish new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:Scottish pop singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish rock singers]]\n[[Category:Scottish singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Scottish soul singers]]\n[[Category:Torch singers]]\n[[Category:Universal Music Group artists]]\n[[Category:British women in electronic music]]\n[[Category:People associated with Glasgow Caledonian University]]\n[[Category:21st-century women singers]]\n[[Category:Ballad musicians]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Scottish Geographical Society]]\n[[Category:The Tourists members]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-semi-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Scottish singer-songwriter}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Annie Lennox<br/><small>[[Order of the British Empire|OBE]]</small>\n| background = solo_singer\n| image = Annie Lennox SING campaign, Vienna 2010 b.jpg\n| caption = Annie Lennox performing at the Rally for Human Rights during the [[International AIDS Conference]] 2010 in [[Vienna]] as part of her [[Sing (Annie Lennox song)|SING Campaign]].\n| birth_name = Ann Lennox\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1954|12|25|df=y}}\n| origin = [[Aberdeen]], Scotland\n| genre = {{flatlist|\n* [[Pop music|Pop]]\n* [[pop rock]]\n* [[rock music|rock]]\n* [[soul music|soul]]\n* [[blue-eyed soul]]\n* [[new wave music|new wave]]\n* [[contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[synth-pop]]\n* [[electronica]]\n* [[adult contemporary music|adult contemporary]]\n* [[jazz]]\n}}\n| occupation = {{flatlist|\n* Singer\n* [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] for [[Glasgow Caledonian University|GCU]]\n* songwriter\n* activist\n* humanitarian ambassador\n}}\n| instrument = {{flatlist|\n* Vocals\n* piano<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first --->\n}}\n| years_active = 1976\u2013present\n| label = {{flatlist|\n* [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n* [[Arista Records|Arista]] <small>(1981\u20132009)</small><br/>[[Island Records|Island]]\n* [[Decca Records|Decca]] <small>(2010\u2013)</small>\n}}\n| associated_acts = {{flatlist|\n* [[The Catch (British band)|The Catch]]\n* [[The Tourists]]\n* [[Eurythmics]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|annielennox.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Ann Lennox''' <small>[[Order of the British Empire|OBE]]</small> (born 25 December 1954) is a Scottish singer-songwriter, political activist and philanthropist. After achieving moderate success in the late 1970s as part of the [[New wave music|new wave]] band [[The Tourists]], she and fellow musician [[Dave Stewart (guitarist)|Dave Stewart]] went on to achieve international success in the 1980s as [[Eurythmics]]. Appearing in the 1983 music video for \u201c[[Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This)]]\u201d with orange cropped hair and wearing a man's business suit, the [[BBC]] states, \"all eyes were on Annie Lennox, the singer whose powerful androgynous look defied the male gaze\".<ref name=\"broke mould\">{{cite news |title=Sweet Dreams: remembering the music video that broke the mould for female pop stars |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/21ftjSTTsg5jnsNsgrj8GZx/sweet-dreams-remembering-the-music-video-that-broke-the-mould-for-female-pop-stars |accessdate=27 September 2019 |agency=BBC}}</ref> Subsequent hits with Eurythmics include \"[[There Must Be an Angel (Playing with My Heart)]]\" and \"[[Here Comes the Rain Again]]\".\n\nLennox embarked on a solo career in 1992 with her debut album, ''[[Diva (Annie Lennox album)|Diva]]'', which produced several hit singles including \"[[Why (Annie Lennox song)|Why]]\" and \"[[Walking on Broken Glass]]\". The same year, she performed \"[[Love Song for a Vampire]]\" for ''[[Bram Stoker's Dracula (1992 film)|Bram Stoker's Dracula]]''. Her 1995 studio album, ''[[Medusa (Annie Lennox album)|Medusa]]'', includes \"[[No More I Love You's (Annie Lennox song)|No More I Love You's]]\" and \"[[A Whiter Shade of Pale#Annie Lennox version|A Whiter Shade of Pale]]\". To date, she has released six solo studio albums and a compilation album, ''[[The Annie Lennox Collection]]'' (2009). With eight [[Brit Awards]], which includes being named [[Brit Award for British Female Solo Artist|Best British Female Artist]] a record six times, Lennox has been named the \"Brits Champion of Champions\".<ref>{{cite news|author =Culture|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/8813544/Annie-Lennox-career-timeline.html|title=Annie Lennox: career timeline|work=The Daily Telegraph|date=7 October 2011|accessdate=26 March 2012|location=London, UK}}</ref> She has also collected four [[Grammy Awards]] and an [[MTV Video Music Award]]. In 2002, Lennox received a [[Billboard Century Award]]; the highest accolade from [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] magazine.<ref name=\"Timeline\"/> In 2004, she received both the [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Golden Globe]] and the [[Academy Award for Best Original Song]] for \"[[Into the West (song)|Into the West]]\", written for the soundtrack to the feature film ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]''.\n\nLennox's vocal range is [[contralto]].<ref name=\"telegraph.co.uk\">Nigel Farndale, [https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/4639351/Annie-Lennox-dont-mess-with-the-missionary-woman.html \"Annie Lennox: don't mess with the missionary woman\"], ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', 20 February 2009</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music/annie-lennox-delivers-nostalgia-pbs-article-1.2162000| title = Annie Lennox delivers 'Nostalgia,' her American songbook, on PBS| work=[[New York Daily News]]| date=27 March 2015| accessdate=27 March 2018| first=Jim| last=Farber}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.billboard.com/articles/grammys-2015/grammy-performances/6465564/grammys-2015-hozier-annie-lennox-mashup| title = Grammys 2015: Hozier & Annie Lennox Mashup 'Take Me to Church/I Put a Spell on You'| work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]| date=8 February 2015| accessdate=27 March 2018| first=Joe| last=Lynch}}</ref> She has been named \"The Greatest White Soul Singer Alive\" by [[VH1]] and one of The 100 Greatest Singers of All Time by ''[[Rolling Stone]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|title=The 100 Greatest Singers of All Time|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/24161972/page/93|newspaper=Rolling Stone|accessdate=14 April 2009|ref=harv|archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090331105405/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/coverstory/24161972/page/93| archivedate=31 March 2009|url-status=live}}</ref> In 2012, she was rated No. 22 on VH1's 100 Greatest Women in Music.<ref name=\"VH1 100\">{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2012-02-13/vh1s-100-greatest-women-in-music-complete-list/ |title=VH1's 100 Greatest Women in Music |work=Music News \u2013 VH1 Music |accessdate=27 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/69AQkBrmL?url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2012-02-13/vh1s-100-greatest-women-in-music-complete-list/ |archivedate=15 July 2012  }}</ref> She has earned the distinction of \"most successful female British artist in UK music history\". {{As of|2008|06}}, including her work with Eurythmics, Lennox had sold over 80&nbsp;million records worldwide.<ref name=\"Macdonell\">{{Cite news|last= Macdonell|first=Hamish|title=Sweet Dreams for SNP as Annie backs independence|url=http://news.scotsman.com/politics/-Sweet-Dreams-for-SNP.4229039.jp|newspaper=[[The Scotsman]]|date=27 June 2008|accessdate=15 April 2009|ref=harv|location=Edinburgh}}</ref> As part of a one-hour symphony of British Music, Lennox performed \"[[Little Bird (Annie Lennox song)|Little Bird]]\" during the [[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony]] in London. At the 2015 [[Ivor Novello Awards]], Lennox was made a fellow of the [[British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors]], the first woman to receive the honour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Annie Lennox Interview|url=https://basca.org.uk/2015/08/18/annie-lennox-interview/|publisher=British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors|accessdate=10 January 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.basca.org.uk/about-us/people/fellows/|title=Fellows \u2013 The British Academy of Songwriters, Composers and Authors|publisher=Basca.org.uk|accessdate=10 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030090735/http://www.basca.org.uk/about-us/people/fellows/|archive-date=30 October 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to her career as a musician, Lennox is also a political and social activist, notable for raising money and awareness for HIV/ AIDS as it affects women and children in Africa. In 2011, Lennox was appointed an [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] by Queen [[Elizabeth II]] for her \"tireless charity campaigns and championing of humanitarian causes\". On 4 June 2012 she performed at the Queen's [[Diamond Jubilee Concert]] in front of [[Buckingham Palace]]. In 2017, Lennox was appointed [[Glasgow Caledonian University]]'s first female chancellor.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-scotland-glasgow-west-42096105|title=Annie Lennox named university chancellor|date=23 November 2017|work=BBC News|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nAnnie Lennox was born on Christmas Day 1954 in Summerfield Maternity Hospital,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pressreader.com/uk/scottish-daily-mail/20120908/283446368622416|title=Annie's Love Life Back on Track|date=8 September 2012|work=Scottish Daily Mail|accessdate=22 December 2018}}</ref> [[Aberdeen]], the daughter of Dorothy Farquharson (n\u00e9e Ferguson; born 1930) and Thomas Allison Lennox (1925\u20131986).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegenealogist.co.uk/treeview/tree_view.php?&tree_id=11936|title=Start building your family tree today|publisher=Thegenealogist.co.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1970s, Lennox won a place at the [[Royal Academy of Music]] in London, where she studied the [[flute]], piano and harpsichord for three years. She lived on a student grant and worked at part-time jobs for extra money. Lennox was unhappy during her time at the Royal Academy and spent her time wondering what other direction she could take.<ref name=\"DIDiscs AL\">{{cite episode|title=Desert Island Discs with Annie Lennox|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio4/factual/desertislanddiscs_20080511.shtml|series=Desert Island Discs|serieslink=Desert Island Discs|network=BBC|station=[[BBC Radio 4|Radio 4]]|airdate=11 May 2008}}</ref>\n\nLennox's flute teacher's final report stated: \"Ann has not always been sure of where to direct her efforts, though lately she has been more committed. She is very, very able, however.\" Two years later, Lennox reported to the Academy: \"I have had to work as a waitress, barmaid, and shop assistant to keep me when not in musical work.\" She also played and sang with a few bands, such as [[Windsong (band)|Windsong]], during the period of her course. In 2006, the academy made her an honorary Fellow.<ref>Royal Academy of Music Bulletin, August 2006, p. 7</ref> Lennox also was made a Fellow of the [[Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama]] that year.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Sutherland|first=Bryony|last2=Ellis|first2=Lucy|year=2002|title=Annie Lennox: The Biography|publisher=Omnibus Press|url=https://books.google.com/?id=AIvGU3nuZL0C|isbn=0-7119-9192-8|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===1976\u20131990: Dragon's Playground, The Tourists and Eurythmics===\n[[File:Eurythmics 06101986 02 270.jpg|thumb|upright=0.81|left|Lennox in the mid-1980s]]\nIn 1976, Lennox was a flute player with a band called Dragon's Playground, leaving before they appeared on TV's ''[[New Faces]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mikedolbear.com/story.asp?StoryID=1691 |title=Mike Dolbear DRUMS |publisher=Mikedolbear.com |accessdate=14 April 2012}}</ref> Between 1977 and 1980, she was the lead singer of [[The Tourists]], a British pop band and her first collaboration with [[David A. Stewart|Dave Stewart]].<ref>[https://www.allmusic.com/artist/the-tourists-mn0000921200/biography \"The Tourists\"]. AllMusic. Retrieved 10 January 2018</ref>\n\nLennox and Stewart's second collaboration, the 1980s [[synthpop]] duo [[Eurythmics]], resulted in her most notable fame, as the duo's [[alto (voice)|alto]], soul-tinged lead singer. Early in Eurythmics' career, Lennox was known for her [[androgyny]],<ref>{{cite news|author =Andrew Anthony|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/10/annie-lennox-eurythmics-christmas-cornucopia-universal-child|title=Annie Lennox: the interview|work=The Observer|accessdate=2 October 2012|location=London, UK|date=10 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Barry|first=Scott|url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/beautiful-minds/200912/george-and-lennox-gaga-and-lambert-androgyny-creativity-and-pop-culture|title=From George and Lennox to Gaga and Lambert: Androgyny, Creativity, and Pop Culture|magazine=Psychology Today|date=2 December 2009|accessdate=2 October 2012}}</ref> wearing suits and once impersonating [[Elvis Presley]]. Eurythmics released a long line of [[single (music)|singles]] in the 1980s, including \"[[Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This)]]\" (a U.S. number one and UK number two), \"[[There Must Be an Angel (Playing with My Heart)]]\" (UK number one), \"[[Love Is A Stranger]]\", \"[[Here Comes the Rain Again]]\", \"[[Sisters Are Doin' It for Themselves]]\", \"[[Who's That Girl? (Eurythmics song)|Who's That Girl?]]\", \"[[Would I Lie to You? (Eurythmics song)|Would I Lie to You?]]\", \"[[Missionary Man (Eurythmics song)|Missionary Man]]\", \"[[You Have Placed a Chill in My Heart]]\", \"[[Thorn in My Side]]\", \"[[The Miracle of Love]]\" and \"[[Don't Ask Me Why (Eurythmics song)|Don't Ask Me Why]]\". Although the Eurythmics never officially disbanded, Lennox made a fairly clear break from Stewart in 1990. Thereafter, she began her solo career.<ref>Martin Strong (1996). \"The Wee Rock Discography\". p. 155., Canongate</ref>\n\n[[File:Eurythmics Rock am Ring 1987.jpg|thumb|right|Lennox (far right) and [[David A. Stewart]] (left) performing as [[Eurythmics]] in 1987.]]\n\nLennox and Stewart reconvened Eurythmics in the late 1990s with the album ''[[Peace (Eurythmics album)|Peace]]'', their first album of new material in ten years. A subsequent concert tour was completed, with profits going to [[Greenpeace]] and [[Amnesty International]].<ref name=\"Timeline\"/> Lennox has received eight [[Brit Awards]], including being named [[Brit Award for British Female Solo Artist|Best British Female Artist]] a record six times.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/1120011.stm|title=Brit Awards: Did you know...?|publisher=News.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Four of the awards were given during her time with Eurythmics, and another was given to the duo for Outstanding Contribution to Music in 1999.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/1999/02/99/brit_awards/280907.stm|title=Brits results in full|publisher=News.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe 1988 single, \"[[Put a Little Love in Your Heart]]\", was a duet with [[Al Green]] recorded for the soundtrack of the movie ''[[Scrooged]]''. Though it was produced by Dave Stewart, it was credited to Lennox and Green. This one-off single peaked at No.&nbsp;9 on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and was a top 40 hit in the UK.<ref name=\"Billboard\">[[Joel Whitburn|Whitburn, Joel]] (2004). The Billboard Book of Top 40 Hits, 8th Edition</ref><ref name=\"UKCharts\">Roberts, David (2006). [[British Hit Singles & Albums]]. London: Guinness World Records Limited</ref> Lennox performed the song \"[[Ev'ry Time We Say Goodbye]]\", a Cole Porter song, that same year for a [[cameo appearance]] in the [[Derek Jarman]] film ''[[Edward II (film)|Edward II]]''. She then appeared with [[David Bowie]] and the surviving members of [[Queen (band)|Queen]] at 1992's [[Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert]] at London's [[Wembley Stadium (1924)|Wembley Stadium]], performing \"[[Under Pressure]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimatequeen.co.uk/videos/fmtributedvd.htm#under|title=Under Pressure \u2013 The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert|publisher=Ultimatequeen.co.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===1992\u20131993: ''Diva''===\n{{Main|Diva (Annie Lennox album)}}\n\nLennox began working with former [[Trevor Horn]] prot\u00e9g\u00e9 [[Stephen Lipson]], beginning with her 1992 solo d\u00e9but album, ''[[Diva (Annie Lennox album)|Diva]]''. It was a commercial and critical success, charting No.&nbsp;1 in the UK, No.&nbsp;6 in Germany, and No.&nbsp;23 in the U.S. where it went [[RIAA certification|double platinum]].<ref name=\"RIAA\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=2&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=queen&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=CertificationDate&perPage=50 |title=RIAA \u2013 Gold and Platinum |work=riaa.com |accessdate=27 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150904041257/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?resultpage=2&table=SEARCH_RESULTS&action=&title=&artist=queen&format=&debutLP=&category=&sex=&releaseDate=&requestNo=&type=&level=&label=&company=&certificationDate=&awardDescription=&catalogNo=&aSex=&rec_id=&charField=&gold=&platinum=&multiPlat=&level2=&certDate=&album=&id=&after=&before=&startMonth=1&endMonth=1&startYear=1958&endYear=2010&sort=CertificationDate&perPage=50 |archivedate=4 September 2015  }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/radio2/events/annielennox/timeline.shtml|title=Annie Lennox in Concert|publisher=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Lennox's profile was boosted by ''Diva'''s singles, which included \"[[Why (Annie Lennox song)|Why]]\" and \"[[Walking on Broken Glass]]\". \"Why\" won an [[MTV Award]] for Best Female Video at the [[1992 MTV Video Music Awards]], while the video for \"Walking on Broken Glass\" set in the [[1750\u201375 in Western fashion|Rococo]] period, featured actors [[Hugh Laurie]] and [[John Malkovich]].<ref name=\"MTVAward\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1992/mtvvmas.htm|title=1992 MTV Video Music Awards|publisher=Rockonthenet.com|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"Video\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Og0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26&q=walking%20on%20broken%20glass%20hugh%20laurie%20john%20malkovich|title=Billboard 7 December 2002|accessdate=27 September 2014|date=7 December 2002}}</ref> \"[[Little Bird (Annie Lennox song)|Little Bird]]\" also formed a double A-side with \"[[Love Song for a Vampire]]\", a soundtrack cut for [[Francis Ford Coppola]]'s 1992 movie ''[[Dracula (1992 film)|Bram Stoker's Dracula]]''.<ref name=\"DraculaOST\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/artists-l/annielennox_main.htm|title=Annie Lennox|publisher=Rockonthenet.com|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> The [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] of her single \"[[Precious (Annie Lennox song)|Precious]]\" was a self-penned song called \"[[Step by Step (Annie Lennox song)|Step by Step]]\", which was later a hit for [[Whitney Houston]] for the [[The Preacher's Wife: Original Soundtrack Album|soundtrack]] of the film ''[[The Preacher's Wife]]''.<ref name=\"DraculaOST\"/> The song \"[[Keep Young and Beautiful (song)|Keep Young and Beautiful]]\" was included on the CD release as a bonus track (the original vinyl album had only ten tracks).\n\nThe album entered the UK album chart at no.1 and has since sold over 1.2&nbsp;million copies in the UK alone, being certified quadruple platinum.<ref name=\"bpi\"/> It was also a success in the US where it was a top 30 hit and has sold in excess of 2,700,000 copies.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> In 1993, the album was included in ''[[Q magazine]]''<nowiki>'</nowiki>s list of the \"50 Best Albums of 1992\". ''[[Rolling Stone (magazine)|Rolling Stone]]'' magazine (25 June 1992, p.&nbsp;41) described the album as \"''...state-of-the-art soul pop...''\" and it is included in Rolling Stone's (13 May 1999, p.&nbsp;56) \"Essential Recordings of the 90's\" list. The album won Best British Album at the 1993 Brit Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brits.co.uk/history/shows/1993|title=The BRITs 1993|publisher=Brit Awards|accessdate=16 December 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101120095723/http://brits.co.uk/history/shows/1993|archivedate=20 November 2010|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===1995\u20132000: ''Medusa'' and return to Eurythmics===\n{{Main|Medusa (Annie Lennox album)|Peace (Eurythmics album)}}\nAlthough Lennox's profile decreased for a period because of her desire to bring up her two children outside of the media's glare, she continued to record. Her second album, ''[[Medusa (Annie Lennox album)|Medusa]]'', was released in March 1995. It consisted solely of [[cover song]]s, all originally recorded by male artists including [[Bob Marley]], [[The Clash]], and [[Neil Young]]. It entered the UK album chart at No.&nbsp;1 and peaked in the US at number 11, spending 60&nbsp;weeks on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] chart and selling over 2,000,000 to date in the United States.<ref name=\"RIAA\"/> It has achieved double platinum status in both the UK and the US.<ref name=\"bpi\">{{cite web|url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |title=Certified Awards Search |publisher=bpi.co.uk |accessdate=16 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090924015932/http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/Search.aspx |archivedate=24 September 2009  }}</ref><ref name=\"riaa\">{{cite web|url=http://www.riaa.org/goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS |title=RIAA Gold and Platinum Database |publisher=Riaa.org |accessdate=27 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100922013600/http://riaa.org//goldandplatinumdata.php?table=SEARCH_RESULTS |archivedate=22 September 2010 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The album yielded four UK singles: \"[[No More I Love You's (Annie Lennox song)|No More I Love You's]]\" (which entered the UK singles chart at No.&nbsp;2, Lennox's highest ever solo peak),<ref name=\"UKCharts\"/> \"[[A Whiter Shade of Pale]]\", \"[[Waiting in Vain]]\" and \"[[Something So Right (song)|Something So Right]]\". The album was nominated for [[Best Pop Vocal Album]] at the [[Grammy Awards of 1996]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/SHOWBIZ/Music/9601/grammy_noms/grammy_list.html|title=CNN \u2013 List of Grammy nominees|date=4 January 1996|publisher=CNN|accessdate=16 December 2010}}</ref> losing to ''[[Turbulent Indigo]]'' by [[Joni Mitchell]], however, Lennox won the Grammy Award for [[Best Female Pop Vocal Performance]] for the single \"No More I Love You's\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockonthenet.com/archive/1996/grammys.htm|title=38th Grammy Awards \u2013 1996|publisher=Rockonthenet.com|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Although Lennox declined to tour for the album, she did perform a large scale one-off concert in New York's [[Central Park]], which was filmed and later released on home video.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/Annie-Lennox-Live-Central-Park/dp/B000055XNQ|title=Amazon.com: Annie Lennox \u2013 Live in Central Park: Annie Lennox|accessdate=16 December 2010}}</ref> Lennox provided an extensive solo vocal performance (without lyrics) for the [[Apollo 13 (film)#Soundtrack|soundtrack]] score of the film ''[[Apollo 13 (film)|Apollo 13]]'' in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmtracks.com/titles/apollo13.html|title=Film Tracks: Apollo 13|publisher=Filmtracks.com|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nManaged by [[Simon Fuller]] since the beginning of her solo career, he said that Lennox played an important but unheralded role in the success of the [[Spice Girls]], encouraging the group to \"ham up\" their characters, which helped them top the charts around the world.<ref>{{cite news |title=Annie Lennox behind the Spice Girls' success, says Simon Fuller |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2014/jan/14/spice-girls-annie-lennox-simon-fuller |date=14 January 2014|accessdate=8 October 2019 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> In 1997, Lennox re-recorded the Eurythmics track \"[[Angel (Eurythmics song)|Angel]]\" for the [[Diana, Princess of Wales: Tribute]] album, and also recorded the song \"Mama\" for ''[[The Avengers (1998 film)|The Avengers]]'' soundtrack album. In 1998, following the death of a mutual friend (former Tourists member [[Peet Coombes]]), she re-united with [[David A. Stewart|Dave Stewart]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9w0EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA26|title=Billboard 25 December 1999 \u2013 1 January 2000|accessdate=27 September 2014|date=25 December 1999 \u2013 1 January 2000}}</ref> Following their first performance together in eight years at a record company party, Stewart and Lennox began writing and recording together for the first time since 1989. This resulted in the album ''[[Peace (Eurythmics album)|Peace]]''. The title was designed to reflect the duo's ongoing concern with global conflict and world peace. The record was promoted with a concert on the [[Greenpeace]] vessel Rainbow Warrior II, where they played a mixture of old and new songs. \"[[I Saved the World Today]]\" was the lead single, reaching number eleven on the [[UK singles chart]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/archive/ |title=The Official Charts Company \u2013 Eurythmics \u2013 I Saved The World Today |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=16 December 2010}}</ref> Another single, released at the beginning of 2000, \"[[17 Again (song)|17 Again]]\", made the UK top 40, and topped the [[Hot Dance Club Play|US dance chart]].<ref>[{{BillboardURLbyName|artist=eurythmics|chart=Dance/Club Play Songs}} Eurythmics Album & Song Chart History] ''Billboard''. 7 November 2011</ref> In 2002, Lennox received a [[Billboard Century Award]]; the highest accolade from [[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']] Magazine, with Editor-in-Chief Timothy White describing her as one of \"the most original and unforgettably affecting artists in the modern annals of popular music.\"<ref name=\"Timeline\"/>\n\n===2003\u20132007: ''Bare'' and work in Africa===\n{{Main|Bare (Annie Lennox album)}}\n[[File:Annie lennox nemahziz.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.9|Annie Lennox on stage in 2004]]\nIn 2003, Lennox released her third solo album, ''[[Bare (Annie Lennox album)|Bare]]''. The album peaked at No.&nbsp;3 in the UK and No.&nbsp;4 in the US \u2013 her highest charting album in the US to date.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/annie-lennox-p24064/charts-awards/billboard-albums |title=Annie Lennox |work=AllMusic |accessdate=16 December 2010}}</ref> She embarked on her first tour as a solo artist to promote the album. The tour, simply titled Solo Tour, pre-dated the release of the album and visited both the US and Europe, with only a two-night stop in the UK at Saddler's Wells Theatre in London. The album has been certified Gold in both the UK and the US and was nominated for [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Vocal Album|Best Pop Album]] at the [[46th Grammy Awards]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.cnn.com/2003-12-04/entertainment/list.grammy.nominations_1_warren-zevon-nelson-and-ray-price-nominees |title=List of major Grammy nominees |publisher=CNN |accessdate=16 December 2010 |date=5 January 1999 }}{{dead link|date=July 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The album was released with a DVD which included interviews and acoustic versions of songs by Lennox.<ref>[http://www.allmusic.com/album/release/bare-bonus-dvd-mr0001207823 \"Bare Bonus DVD\"]. All music. Retrieved 9 December 2014</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Lennox won the [[Academy Award for Best Song]] for \"[[Into the West (song)|Into the West]]\" from the film ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thegospelaccordingtorichardcroft.wordpress.com/2010/04/30/238-annie-lennox-into-the-west-2003/ |title=238. Annie Lennox \u2013 'Into The West' (2003) \" The Gospel According To Richard Croft 1001 Songs That Are Good |work=thegospelaccordingtorichardcroft.wordpress.com |accessdate=16 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718111547/http://thegospelaccordingtorichardcroft.wordpress.com/2010/04/30/238-annie-lennox-into-the-west-2003/ |archivedate=18 July 2011  }}</ref> which she co-wrote with screenwriter [[Fran Walsh]] and composer [[Howard Shore]]. Lennox performed the song live at the [[76th Academy Awards]]. The song also won a Grammy award and a [[Golden Globe]] award. She had previously recorded \"Use Well the Days\" for the movie, which incorporates a number of quotations from [[J. R. R. Tolkien|Tolkien]] in its lyrics. This features on a bonus DVD included with the \"special edition\" of the movie's soundtrack CD. In mid-2004, Lennox embarked on an extensive North American tour with [[Sting (musician)|Sting]].<ref name=\"Timeline\"/> In July 2005, Lennox performed at [[Live 8]] in [[Hyde Park, London]], along with [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], Sting, and other popular musicians.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/thelive8event/lineupandartists/|title=Live 8: Line up of the artists|publisher=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Lennox and Stewart collaborated on two new songs for their Eurythmics compilation album, ''[[Ultimate Collection (Eurythmics album)|Ultimate Collection]]'', of which \"[[I've Got a Life]]\" was released as a single in October 2005. The promotional video for the song features Lennox and Stewart performing in the present day, with images of past Eurythmics videos playing on television screens behind them. The single peaked at number fourteen in the [[UK Singles Chart]] and was a number-one US [[Hot Dance Club Play|Dance hit]].<ref name=\"Billboard\"/><ref name=\"UKCharts\"/> On 14 November 2005, Sony BMG repackaged and released Eurythmics' back catalogue as 2005 Deluxe Edition Reissues.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/eurythmics-ultimate-collection/id303097824|title=Eurythmics: Ultimate Collection (Remastered)|work=iTunes|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Lennox also collaborated with [[Herbie Hancock]] doing the song \"Hush, Hush, Hush\" on his collaboration album, ''[[Possibilities]]'' in August 2005.<ref>{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=album|id=r788408|pure_url=yes}} |title=Possibilities > Charts & Awards > Billboard Albums |accessdate=9 December 2014 |work=[[AllMusic]]}}</ref>\n\n===2007\u20132008: ''Songs of Mass Destruction'' and AIDS activism===\n{{Main|Songs of Mass Destruction}}\n\nEnding her long association with [[Stephen Lipson]], Lennox's fourth solo album, ''[[Songs of Mass Destruction]]'', was recorded in Los Angeles with veteran producer [[Glen Ballard]] (known for producing [[Alanis Morissette]]'s album, ''[[Jagged Little Pill]]''). It was released on 1 October 2007, and was the last studio album of Lennox's contract with [[Bertelsmann Music Group|BMG]]. It peaked at No.&nbsp;7 in the UK and No.&nbsp;9 in the US.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/><ref name=\"UKCharts\"/> Lennox stated that she believed the album consisted of \"twelve strong, powerful, really emotive songs that people can connect to\". If she achieves that, she says, \"I can feel proud of [it], no matter if it sells ten copies or 50 million.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/news/58022/annie-lennox-gets-busy-on-new-album | title=Annie Lennox Gets Busy on New Album | author=Newman, Melinda |work=Billboard  | date=23 June 2006 | accessdate=29 June 2006 | ref=harv}}</ref> Lennox described it as \"a dark album, but the world is a dark place. It's fraught, it's turbulent. Most people's lives are underscored with dramas of all kinds: there's ups, there's downs \u2013 the flickering candle.\"<ref name=PCOLTelegraph>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/arts/main.jhtml;jsessionid=D20QKPK3BFB55QFIQMFSFF4AVCBQ0IV0?xml=/arts/2007/09/20/bmannie120.xml|title=\"Annie Lennox: Diva singing through the darkness.\" 20 September 2007.|work=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> She added, \"Half the people are drinking or drugging themselves to numb it. A lot of people are in pain.\"<ref name=PCOLTelegraph/>\n\nThe album's first single was \"[[Dark Road (song)|Dark Road]]\", released on 24 September 2007. Another song on the album, \"[[Sing (Annie Lennox song)|Sing]]\", is a collaboration between Lennox and 23 prominent female artists: [[Anastacia]], [[Isobel Campbell]], [[Dido (singer)|Dido]], [[C\u00e9line Dion]], [[Melissa Etheridge]], [[Fergie (singer)|Fergie]], [[Beth Gibbons]], [[Faith Hill]], [[Angelique Kidjo]], [[Beverley Knight]], [[Gladys Knight]], [[k.d. lang]], [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]], [[Sarah McLachlan]], [[Beth Orton]], [[Pink (singer)|Pink]], [[Kelis]], [[Bonnie Raitt]], [[Shakira]], [[Shingai Shoniwa]], [[Joss Stone]], [[Sugababes]], [[KT Tunstall]], and [[Martha Wainwright]]. The song was recorded to raise money and awareness for the HIV/AIDS organisation [[Treatment Action Campaign]].<ref name=\"Sing\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/7027966.stm|title=Aids fight inspires singer Lennox|date=5 October 2007|work=BBC News|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Included among the group of vocalists are TAC activist members' own vocal group known as The Generics, whose CD of music inspired Lennox to make \"Sing\".<ref name=\"Sing\"/> To promote ''Songs of Mass Destruction'', Lennox embarked on a primarily North American tour called Annie Lennox Sings, which lasted throughout October and November 2007.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/09/30/arts/music/30pare.html The Return of the Sweet Dreamer] ''The New York Times''. Retrieved 8 November 2011</ref>\n\n===2008\u20132009: ''The Annie Lennox Collection'' and departure from Sony===\n{{Main|The Annie Lennox Collection}}\nFinishing out her contract with Sony BMG, Lennox released the compilation album ''[[The Annie Lennox Collection]]''. Initially intended for release in September 2008, the release date was pushed back several months to allow Lennox to recuperate from a back injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/music/annie-lennox-from-the-eurythmics-talks-about-new-album/story-e6frexl9-1225690039466|title=Annie Lennox from the Eurythmics talks about new album|publisher=Dailytelegraph.com.au|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> The compilation was eventually released in the US on 17 February 2009, and in the UK and Europe on 9 March 2009. Included on the track listing are songs from her four solo albums, one from the ''[[Dracula (1992 film)|Bram Stoker's Dracula]]'' soundtrack, and two new songs. One of these is a cover of [[Ash (band)|Ash's]] single, \"[[Shining Light]]\". The other is a cover of a song by the English band [[Keane (band)|Keane]], originally the B-side of their first single in 2000. Lennox renamed the song from its original title \"[[Call Me What You Like#Closer Now|Closer Now]]\" to \"[[Pattern of My Life]]\". A limited 3-disc edition of the album included a DVD compilation featuring most of Lennox's solo videos since 1992, and also featured a second CD of rarer songs including a version of [[R.E.M.]]'s \"[[Everybody Hurts]]\" with [[Alicia Keys]] and Lennox's Oscar-winning \"Into the West\" from the third ''Lord of the Rings'' film. The album entered the [[UK Album Chart]] at No.&nbsp;2 and remained in the top 10 for seven weeks.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.officialcharts.com/archive/ |title=Annie Lennox: The Collection |publisher=[[Official Charts Company]] |accessdate=27 September 2014 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140921151153/http://www.officialcharts.com/archive/ |archive-date=21 September 2014 }}</ref>\n\nLennox's recording contract with [[Sony BMG]] concluded with the release of ''Songs of Mass Destruction'' and the subsequent retrospective album ''The Collection'', and much was made in the press in late 2007/early 2008 about the apparent animosity between Lennox and the record company. Lennox stated that while on a trip to South Africa in December 2007 to appear at the [[46664 (concerts)|46664]] campaign in Johannesburg, the regional company office of the label failed to return phone calls and e-mails she made to them for three weeks, and had completely failed to promote the Sing project as planned. Upon her return to the UK, Lennox met with the head of Sony BMG UK, Ged Docherty, who was \"mortified\" by the problems she had encountered with the South African branch. However, the debacle (partly inflamed when Lennox's dissatisfaction with the South African office was made public on her blog) led to press reports falsely stating that she was being dropped by Sony BMG. The record company themselves quickly refuted the rumour stating that Lennox's contract with them had merely been fulfilled and that they hoped she would consider remaining with them. The British tabloid, ''[[Daily Mirror]]'', subsequently printed a retraction of its story about her being dropped by the label.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.annielennox.com/news.php?newsItem=871 |title=Official press statement Jan 2008 |publisher=Annielennox.com |date=15 January 2008 |accessdate=27 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707145210/http://www.annielennox.com/news.php?newsItem=871 |archivedate=7 July 2011  }}</ref>\n\n===2010\u20132013: Island Records and ''A Christmas Cornucopia''===\n{{main|A Christmas Cornucopia}}\nIn August 2010, Lennox signed a new contract with [[Island Records]] in the UK and [[Decca Records]] in the US (both part of the [[Universal Music Group]]).<ref>[http://www.universalmusic.com/corporate/international-superstar-annie-lennox-signs-with-universal-music-group-umg-for-worldwide-re International Superstar Annie Lennox signs with Universal Music Group (UMG)] Universal Music. Retrieved 8 November 2011</ref> Her first release was a Christmas album entitled ''[[A Christmas Cornucopia]]'', issued on 15 November 2010. The album is a collection of Lennox's interpretations of traditional festive songs such as \"[[Silent Night]]\" and \"[[The First Noel]]\", along with one new composition, \"[[Universal Child]]\", which was released as a download-only single on 13 October 2010. Lennox had previously showcased the song on the ''[[Idol Gives Back|American Idol Gives Back]]'' TV show in April 2010. She sang the song \"[[Angels from the Realms of Glory]]\" from the album for the TNT special ''[[Christmas in Washington]]''.<ref name=\"angelsfromtherealmsofglory\">{{cite episode |title=Christmas in Washington 2010 |url=http://www.tnt.tv/christmasinwashington/ |series=Christmas in Washington |serieslink=Christmas in Washington |airdate=17 December 2010 |credits=DeGeneres, Ellen (Host); Bocelli, Andrea (Performer); Carey, Mariah (Performer); Cosgrove, Miranda (Performer); Maxwell (Performer); Morrison, Matthew (Performer); Lennox, Annie (Performer) |network=TNT |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101123012651/http://www.tnt.tv/christmasinwashington/ |archivedate=23 November 2010  }}</ref>\n\nA music video was produced for a second single from the album, \"[[God Rest Ye Merry Gentlemen]]\". Lennox also performed the track on the UK chat show ''[[Loose Women]]'' in December 2010, and was also interviewed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/lifestyle/loosewomen/videos/a/celebrityguests/annielennox|title=\"Annie Lennox \u2013 The singing legend talks about her Christmas Cornucopia album\" on \"Loose Women\"|work=ITV Player|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> According to [[Metacritic]], ''A Christmas Cornucopia'' has gained \"generally favourable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/a-christmas-cornucopia|title=Reviews|publisher=Metacritic.com|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Ian Wade of [[BBC Music]] gave the album a very positive review, saying \"this collection could find itself becoming as much a part of the holiday season as arguments with loved ones.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/music/reviews/65fd|title=Annie Lennox A Christmas Cornucopia Review|publisher=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> Sal Cinquemani of ''[[Slant Magazine]]'' awarded the album 3.5/5 and said \"Lennox seems more inspired on ''A Christmas Cornucopia'' than she has in years.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slantmagazine.com/music/review/annie-lennox-a-christmas-cornucopia/2324|title=Album review|author =Sal Cinquemani|date=18 November 2010|work=Slant Magazine|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> John Hunt of ''Qatar Today'' magazine gave the album 9/10 and said \"in particular, the vocal work and musical arrangement of 'God Rest Ye Merry Gentlemen' are impactful to the point of being intimidating.\"<ref>''Qatar Today'', Jan 2011, Music, Books and Film</ref>\n\nOn 4 June 2012, Lennox performed, as part of the Queen's [[Diamond Jubilee Concert]], in front of [[Buckingham Palace]] in London and on 12 August she performed \"[[Little Bird (Annie Lennox song)|Little Bird]]\" at the [[2012 Summer Olympics Closing Ceremony]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/rockandpopreviews/9467519/Olympic-Closing-Ceremony-London-2012-review.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | first=Bernadette | last=McNulty | title=Olympic Closing Ceremony London 2012: review | date=12 August 2012}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u2013present: ''Nostalgia''===\nIn October 2014, Lennox released her sixth solo album, ''[[Nostalgia (Annie Lennox album)|Nostalgia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Lennox|first=Annie|url=http://www.annielennox.com/blog/new-album-nostalgia-coming-soon/|title=New Album \u2013 NOSTALGIA \u2013 Coming Soon|publisher=annielennox.com|accessdate=15 August 2014|date=15 August 2014}}</ref> The album is a collection of Lennox's childhood favourite soul, jazz and blues songs.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tan|first=Young|url=http://sosogay.co.uk/2014/annie-lennox-release-new-album-nostalgia/|title=Annie Lennox to release new album 'Nostalgia'|publisher=So So Gay|accessdate=16 August 2014|date=15 August 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819085747/http://sosogay.co.uk/2014/annie-lennox-release-new-album-nostalgia/|archivedate=19 August 2014}}</ref> Critic Mike Wass of ''Idolator'' stated that Lennox \"puts her own inimitable spin\" on the selected tracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.idolator.com/7530641/annie-lennox-previews-new-covers-album-nostalgia |title=Annie Lennox Previews New Covers LP 'Nostalgia' At Hollywood Forever Cemetery in LA |author =Wass, Mike |date=13 August 2014 |publisher=Idolator |accessdate=16 August 2014}}</ref> The [[lead single]] \"[[I Put a Spell on You]]\" received its first radio play on 15 September 2014 by [[Ken Bruce]] on [[BBC Radio 2]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b04gynqd|title=Tony Blackburn picks the Tracks of My Years|publisher=BBC Radio 2|accessdate=15 September 2014|date=15 September 2014}}</ref> Upon release, the album entered the UK and US Top 10, and reached number one on the US [[Billboard Top Jazz Albums]] chart. The album was nominated for a [[Grammy Award]] for [[Best Traditional Pop Vocal Album]]. On 28 January 2015, Lennox performed a live concert at the [[Orpheum Theatre (Los Angeles)|Orpheum Theatre]] in Los Angeles entitled ''An Evening of Nostalgia with Annie Lennox''. The show aired on [[PBS]] in the US in April 2015, and was released on DVD and Blu-ray internationally in May 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annielennox.com/news/nostalgia-an-evening-with-annie-lennox-to-be-released-on-dvd/|title=Nostalgia: An Evening With Annie Lennox Live OUT NOW!|work=Annie Lennox}}</ref>\n\n==Public image==\n\n===Charity and political activism===\n[[File:Annie Lennox DNP.jpg|thumb|right|[[HIV]] campaigner Lennox in Germany ahead of [[World AIDS Day]] in 2008]]\nLennox appeared on stage at the 1988 [[Nelson Mandela]] 70th Birthday Concert and commenced activist work with the Sing Foundation afterwards.<ref>{{cite news|title=Nelson Mandela memorial guest list|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/nelson-mandela/10507035/Nelson-Mandela-memorial-guest-list.html|accessdate=21 December 2013|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=10 December 2013|author =Natasha Clark|location=London}}</ref> In 1990, Lennox recorded a version of [[Cole Porter]]'s \"[[Ev'ry Time We Say Goodbye]]\" for the Cole Porter tribute album ''[[Red Hot + Blue]]'', a benefit for AIDS awareness. A video was also produced.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mvdbase.com/video.php?id=16390 | title=mvdbase.com \u2013 Annie Lennox \u2013 \"Every time we say goodbye\" | accessdate=15 December 2010}}</ref> Lennox has been a public supporter of [[Amnesty International]] and [[Greenpeace]] for many years, and she and Dave Stewart donated all of the profits from Eurythmics' 1999 Peacetour to both charities.<ref>{{Cite journal |title = Peace core{{sic|hide=yes}} |url=https://www.heraldscotland.com/news/12205739.peace-core| journal=The Herald|location=Glasgow |page = 16 |date = 24 November 1999 |ref = harv}}</ref> Concerned by [[Tibet]] freedom,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tibetsociety.com/content/view/131/|title=Messages for Dalai Lama's 75th birthday|author=User 2|publisher=Tibetsociety.com|accessdate=27 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160307041010/http://tibetsociety.com/content/view/131|archive-date=7 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> she supported Amnesty International campaigns for the release of Tibetan prisoners [[Palden Gyatso]] and [[Ngawang Choephel]].<ref>[[Thor Halvorssen Mendoza]], [https://www.forbes.com/sites/thorhalvorssen/2012/02/23/and-the-nominees-for-outstanding-performance-in-the-service-of-human-rights-are/4/ And the Nominees for Outstanding Performance in the Service of Human Rights Are...], 23 February 2012</ref>\n\nIn 2006, in response to her humanitarian work, Lennox became patron of the Master's Course in ''Humanitarian and Development Practice'' for [[Oxford Brookes University]].<ref name=\"Timeline\"/> In October 2006, Lennox spoke at the [[British House of Commons]] about the need for children in the UK to help their counterparts in Africa.<ref name=\"Timeline\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/8813544/Annie-Lennox-career-timeline.html|title=Annie Lennox: career timeline|date=7 October 2011|work=Telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> On 25 April 2007, Lennox performed \"[[Bridge over Troubled Water (song)|Bridge over Troubled Water]]\" during the ''[[American Idol]]'' \"Idol Gives Back\" fundraising drive.<ref>[http://www.americanidol.me.uk/annie-lennox-bridge-over-troubled-water-live-on-american-idol-gives-back-2007.html Annie Lennox Bridge Over Troubled Water Live on American Idol Gives Back 2007] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111103074113/http://www.americanidol.me.uk/annie-lennox-bridge-over-troubled-water-live-on-american-idol-gives-back-2007.html |date=3 November 2011 }} American Idol. Retrieved 8 November 2011</ref> Lennox's 2007 song \"[[Sing (Annie Lennox song)|Sing]]\" was born out of her involvement with [[Nelson Mandela]]'s 46664 campaign and [[Treatment Action Campaign]] (TAC), both of which are human rights groups which seek education and health care for those affected by HIV.<ref name=\"Timeline\"/><ref name=\"Sing\"/> In December 2007, Lennox established [[The SING Campaign]], an organisation dedicated to raising funds and awareness for women and children affected by HIV and AIDS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annielennoxsing.com|title=SING website|website=Annielennoxsing.com|accessdate=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n[[File:Memory and Annie call on UK to lead efforts to bring end to AIDS.jpg|thumb|left|HIV campaigners, Memory Sachikonye (left) and Lennox (right) meet with the UK's [[Secretary of State for International Development]] [[Andrew Mitchell]] in December 2011]]\nOn 11 December 2007, she performed in the [[Nobel Peace Prize Concert]] in [[Oslo, Norway]] together with a variety of artists, which was broadcast to over 100 countries.<ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://nobelpeaceprize.org/concert/ |title=Nobel Peace Prize Concert 2007 |accessdate=11 December 2007 |publisher=Nobel Peace Prize |ref=harv |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071207223134/http://nobelpeaceprize.org/concert |archivedate=7 December 2007 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Lennox appeared at the Nelson Mandela 90th Birthday Tribute in June 2008<ref>{{cite news|title=Nelson Mandela birthday tribute concerts: how they helped change the world|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/nelson-mandela/10155341/Nelson-Mandela-birthday-tribute-concerts-how-they-helped-change-the-world.html|accessdate=21 December 2013|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=6 December 2013|author =Rupert Hawksley|location=London}}</ref> and then led a rally against the [[Gaza War (2008\u201309)|Gaza War]] in London on 3 January 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.looktothestars.org/news/1842-annie-lennox-protests-carnage-in-gaza|title=Annie Lennox Protests Carnage in Gaza|author =Tim Saunders|work=looktothestars.org|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nLennox opened the 2009 Edinburgh Festival of Politics with commentary on Pope [[Benedict XVI]]'s approach to HIV/AIDS prevention in Africa. She said that the Pope's denunciation of condoms on his recent tour of Africa had caused \"tremendous harm\" and she criticised the Roman Catholic Church for causing widespread confusion on the continent. Lennox also condemned the media's obsession with \"celebrity culture\" for keeping the AIDS pandemic off the front page. During her address, Lennox wore a T-shirt emblazoned with the words \"HIV positive\". Lennox wore similar T-shirts at the 25th Anniversary Rock & Roll Hall of Fame concert at Madison Square Garden on 30 October 2009,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://insidetv.aol.com/2009/11/30/annie-lennox-wears-hiv-positive-t-shirt-onstage-with-aretha/ |title=Annie Lennox Wears 'HIV Positive' T-Shirt Onstage With Aretha (VIDEO) |publisher=Insidetv.aol.com |accessdate=27 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091205031451/http://insidetv.aol.com/2009/11/30/annie-lennox-wears-hiv-positive-t-shirt-onstage-with-aretha |archivedate=5 December 2009  }}</ref> during her appearance on ''[[The Graham Norton Show]]'' on 30 November 2009 (where she performed the new song \"Full Steam\", a duet with singer [[David Gray (musician)|David Gray]]), during a recorded performance for ''[[American Idol]]'' during a 21 April 2010 fundraiser, entitled [[Idol Gives Back]], and during a performance on the live [[Comic Relief]] show on 18 March 2011.\n\n{{Quote box|width=28%|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|align=right|quote=\"She is one of those exemplary human beings who chose to put her success in her chosen career to work in order to benefit others. She is a true friend of Africa and of South Africa. Her Aids activism in general, and support for the treatment action campaign in-particular, contributed significantly to turning the pandemic around in our country.\"|source=\u2014Archbishop [[Desmond Tutu]] pays tribute to Annie Lennox in November 2013.<ref name=\"Trusts\">[http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/providing-soundtrack-to-our-lives-annie-lennox-feted-by-tutu-elton-adele.1383635672  \"Providing soundtrack to our lives: Annie Lennox feted by Tutu, Elton, Adele\"]. Sunday Herald. Retrieved 12 November 2014</ref>}} In June 2010, Lennox was named as a [[UNESCO Goodwill Ambassador]] for AIDS,<ref>{{cite web|author =Chris Watt |url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/home-news/lennox-appointed-un-ambassador-in-fight-against-aids-1.1032473|title=Lennox appointed UN ambassador in fight against AIDS|work=The Herald|location=Glasgow|date=3 June 2010|accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref> a role that continues {{as of|2013|August|lc=y}}. Lennox also works with other organisations such as Oxfam, Amnesty International and the British Red Cross in regard to the issue.<ref>{{cite news|title=Annie Lennox on How to 'Catch' Creative Ideas|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/video/archive/2013/08/annie-lennox-on-how-to-catch-creative-ideas/279101/|accessdate=8 September 2013|newspaper=The Atlantic Monthly|date=28 August 2013|author =Emma Green}}</ref> Lennox also supports the [[Burma Campaign UK]], a [[NGO|non-governmental organisation]] that addresses the suffering in [[Burma]] and promotes democratisation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burmacampaign.org.uk/index.php/news-and-reports/news-stories/Annie-Lennox-and-Faithless-on-the-crisis-in-Burma/4|title=Annie Lennox and Faithless on the crisis in Burma|publisher=Burmacampaign.org.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, it was confirmed that Lennox was in the [[2011 New Year Honours|New Years Honours List]] and would become an [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in recognition of her humanitarian work. She received the award from Queen [[Elizabeth II]] at Buckingham Palace on 28 June 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/showbiz/celebrity-news/2010/12/31/annie-lennox-and-disabled-mp-anne-begg-the-leading-scots-in-new-year-s-honours-list-86908-22817150/|title=Annie Lennox and disabled MP Anne Begg the leading Scots in New Year's Honours list|work=dailyrecord|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://edition.cnn.com/2010/WORLD/europe/12/31/uk.honors.list/ | publisher=CNN | title=Sweet dreams for Annie Lennox in queen's honors list | date=31 December 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2013, Lennox received the Music Industry Trusts Award for her career achievements in music and her charity commitments.<ref name=\"Trusts\"/> [[Elton John]] said of her award; \"It is so well deserved and not only for your extraordinary contribution to music and songwriting but also for your outstanding and tireless work as an HIV and AIDS activist and supporter of women's rights,\" while [[Adele]] stated; \"Annie Lennox has been a constant part of my life. An example of a brilliant talent that exudes excellence and influence on everyone.\"<ref name=\"Trusts\"/>\n\nIn 2015 Lennox attended, performed at and hosted several charitable events including: the 50th [[Amnesty International]] Annual Conference where she was a guest speaker, Elton John and David Furnish's at home Gala in aid of the [[Elton John Aids Foundation]] where she performed, held a screening of [[He Named Me Malala]], and hosted a [[Mothers2mothers]] 15th Anniversary gala. In 2016 Lennox was awarded the [[Elle Style Awards]] 'Outstanding Achievement' award, and the [[Royal Scottish Geographical Society]] award, the [[Livingstone Medal]], in recognition of her outstanding contribution to the fight against AIDS and support of women's rights.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unaids.org/en/resources/presscentre/featurestories/2016/march/20160318_Lennox|title=Annie Lennox awarded prestigious Livingstone Medal|publisher=UNAIDS|accessdate= 1 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Relationship with the LGBT+ Community===\n[[File:Annie Lennox Rock am Ring 1987.jpg|thumb|upright|Lennox was known for her [[androgyny]] during the 1980s]]\nLennox's longtime support for [[LGBT]] rights have helped garner a significant following within the community.<ref name=\"Independent 2014-10-30\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/annie-lennox-on-being-mistaken-for-a-lesbian-i-think-intelligent-heterosexual-women-are-challenging-9828047.html |title=Annie Lennox on being mistaken for a lesbian |date=30 October 2014 |website=[[The Independent]]}}</ref> According to ''[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]]'', \"her distinctive voice and provocative stage persona have made Lennox a longtime [[gay icon]].\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid49737.asp |title=Annie Lennox to Host Logo's Music Show |date=13 October 2007 |work=[[The Advocate (LGBT magazine)|The Advocate]] |access-date=12 April 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090620102445/http://www.advocate.com/news_detail_ektid49737.asp |archive-date=20 June 2009 |url-status=dead |ref=harv}}</ref> \n\nKnown for her androgynous look in the 1980s \u2013 first widely seen in the 1983 music video for \"[[Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This)]]\" where she had close-cropped, orange-coloured hair, and wore a man's suit brandishing a cane, a video which made her a household name \u2013 Lennox was viewed as the female version of Boy George, and during the [[Second British Invasion]] spurred by MTV, ''[[Newsweek]]'' magazine ran an issue which featured Lennox and Boy George on the cover of its 23 January 1984 edition with the caption ''Britain Rocks America&nbsp;\u2013 Again''.<ref>Simon Reynolds, Rip It Up and Start Again Postpunk 1978\u20131984, pp. 340, 342\u20133.</ref>\n\n===Exhibition===\nIn conjunction with the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] in London, Lennox put many items from her collection\u2014costumes, accessories, photographs, awards, ephemera from her political campaigns, and personal belongings\u2014on display. This collection, which spanned her entire career, along with music videos and interviews, became ''The House of Annie Lennox'' at the V+A from 15 September 2011 to 26 February 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vam.ac.uk/content/articles/p/past-exhibitions-and-displays-2011/|title=Past exhibitions & displays 2011|publisher=Vam.ac.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref> An expanded version of the exhibit was later installed at [[The Lowry]] in [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]] from 17 March 2012 to 17 June,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fxs09u9w3NY|title=The House of Annie Lennox \u2013 Interview with Annie|work=YouTube|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thelowry.com/events/the-house-of-annie-lennox/home/|title=Exhibit dates|publisher=Thelowry.com|accessdate=27 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006081122/http://www.thelowry.com/events/the-house-of-annie-lennox/home/|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref> before moving to Aberdeen for twelve weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aberdeencity.gov.uk/CouncilNews/ci_cns/pr_annielennox_270912.asp|title=Aberdeen City Council \u2013 Annie Lennox exhibition (27 Sep 2012)|website=Aberdeencity.gov.uk|accessdate=30 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Music videos==\n{{quote box|width=27%|bgcolor=#c6dbf7|align=right|quote=\"The video accompanying \"Sweet Dreams (Are Made of This)\u201d, in which Annie Lennox appeared with closely cropped orange hair and wearing a man\u2019s business suit, was both striking and surreal. Lennox\u2019s extraordinary image was at odds with her female contemporaries\".|source=\u2014Sweet Dreams: remembering the music video that broke the mould for female pop stars, ([[BBC]]).<ref name=\"broke mould\"/>}}\n{{See also|Annie Lennox discography#Music videos|l1=Annie Lennox music videos}}\nBoth as part of Eurythmics and in her solo career, Lennox has made over 60 music promo videos. The 1987 Eurythmics album ''[[Savage (Eurythmics album)|Savage]]'' and her 1992 solo album ''[[Diva (Annie Lennox album)|Diva]]'' were both accompanied by video albums, both directed by [[Sophie Muller]].<ref>(VHS) Totally Diva. [[Sony BMG]].</ref> Actors [[Hugh Laurie]] and [[John Malkovich]] appeared in the music video for \"[[Walking on Broken Glass]]\" in period costume, while the video for \"[[Little Bird (Annie Lennox song)|Little Bird]]\" paid homage to the different images and personas that have appeared in some of Lennox's previous videos.<ref name=\"Video\"/> The clip features Lennox performing on stage with several lookalikes (male and female) that represent her personas from \"Why\", \"Walking on Broken Glass\", \"Sweet Dreams\", \"Beethoven (I Love To Listen To)\", \"I Need a Man\", \"Thorn in My Side\", \"There Must Be an Angel\", and even her stage image from the 1992 [[Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Annie Lennox \u2013 Little Bird (1993) |url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2b844db119 |accessdate=14 June 2019 |agency=BFI}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nLennox has been married three times. Her first marriage, from 1984 to 1985, was to German [[International Society for Krishna Consciousness|Hare Krishna]] devotee Radha Raman.<ref name=Sutherland209>{{Harvnb|Sutherland|Ellis|2002|pp=209\u2013217}}</ref> From 1988 to 2000, she was married to [[Israelis|Israeli]] film and record producer [[Uri Fruchtmann]].<ref name=\"Observer 2010\">{{cite news|last=Anthony|first=Andrew|title=Annie Lennox: 'I would have been perfect as a man'|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2010/oct/10/annie-lennox-eurythmics-christmas-cornucopia-universal-child|accessdate=11 November 2010|newspaper=The Observer|date=10 October 2010|location=London| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101023210318/http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2010/oct/10/annie-lennox-eurythmics-christmas-cornucopia-universal-child|archivedate= 23 October 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> The couple have two daughters, Lola and [[Tali Lennox|Tali]]. A son, Daniel, was stillborn in 1988.<ref>{{cite news|last=Hastings|first=Chris|title=Annie Lennox: Son's death changed my life|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/celebritynews/1944539/Annie-Lennox-Sons-death-changed-my-life.html|accessdate=27 October 2013|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=10 May 2008|location=London}}</ref> On 15 September 2012, Lennox married Mitch Besser in London in a private ceremony.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.people.com/people/article/0,,20630971,00.html |title=Annie Lennox Marries Dr. Mitch Besser : People.com |date=15 March 2016 |access-date=14 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160315212510/http://www.people.com/people/article/0%2C%2C20630971%2C00.html |archivedate=15 March 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.alliancemagazine.org/interview/interview-annie-lennox-and-mitch-besser/|title=Interview \u2013 Annie Lennox and Mitch Besser \u2013 Alliance magazine|website=Alliance magazine|language=en-US|access-date=14 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Lennox featured in Series 9 of the BBC's ''[[Who Do You Think You Are? (British TV series)|Who Do You Think You Are?]]'', in which she discovered that her great-great-grandmother Jessie Fraser worked at the [[Flax mill|Broadford Flax Mill]] in Aberdeen. Her maternal grandmother, Dora Paton, was a dairy maid at the [[Balmoral Castle|Balmoral Royal Estate]] and her maternal grandfather, William Ferguson, was a [[gamekeeper]] also at Balmoral.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01mhh17|title=\"Who Do You Think You Are? \u2013 Annie Lennox\" at bbc.co.uk|work=BBC|accessdate=27 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nBoth of Lennox's parents died of cancer.<ref name=\"DIDiscs AL\"/> Lennox is an [[agnostic]]<ref>{{cite news|author =Lennox, Annie|title=Annie Lennox on the Secret History of Christmas Songs|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2010/12/18/annie-lennox-on-how-to-write-a-christmas-carol/|date=18 December 2010|publisher=Dow Jones|work=The Wall Street Journal|accessdate=24 December 2010}}</ref> and a [[Feminism|feminist]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Muller, Marissa G.|title=Annie Lennox Says Twerking Has Nothing to Do with Feminism|url=http://radio.com/2014/10/21/annie-lennox-twerking-not-feminism/|date=21 October 2014|work=Radio.com|accessdate=31 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150426221256/http://radio.com/2014/10/21/annie-lennox-twerking-not-feminism/|archive-date=26 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> In the 2010 ''[[Sunday Times Rich List]]'' of British millionaires from the world of music, Lennox was estimated to have a fortune of \u00a330 million.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.iptegrity.com/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=510&Itemid=9 | title= Musicians coining it in Sunday Times Rich List}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n{{Main|Annie Lennox discography}}\n{{See also|Eurythmics discography}}\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n===Studio albums===\n* ''[[Diva (Annie Lennox album)|Diva]]'' (1992)\n* ''[[Medusa (Annie Lennox album)|Medusa]]'' (1995)\n* ''[[Bare (Annie Lennox album)|Bare]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Songs of Mass Destruction]]'' (2007)\n* ''[[A Christmas Cornucopia]]'' (2010)\n* ''[[Nostalgia (Annie Lennox album)|Nostalgia]]'' (2014)\n{{col-break}}\n\n===Compilation albums===\n* ''[[The Annie Lennox Collection]]'' (2009)\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\nLennox has received a variety of major awards during her career:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annielennox.com |title=Many of Annie Lennox's awards are viewable on her official website in the memorabilia/awards room |publisher=Annielennox.com |date=15 October 2010 |accessdate=27 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101206180756/http://www.annielennox.com/| archivedate= 6 December 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n\n===Academy Awards===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:70%;\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4%;