t Female Video]]\n|{{won}}\n|-\n| [[1993 MTV Video Music Awards|1993]]\n| \"[[Walking on Broken Glass]]\"\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[1996 MTV Video Music Awards|1996]]\n| \"[[No More 'I Love You's]]\"\n|{{nom}}\n|}\n\n; [[American Music Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annielennox.com |title=American Music Awards listed on official website |publisher=Annielennox.com |date=15 October 2010 |accessdate=27 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101206180756/http://www.annielennox.com/| archivedate= 6 December 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n*[[American Music Awards of 2008|2008]] \u2013 AMA Award of Merit for her work and her humanitarian efforts\n\n; [[Ivor Novello Awards]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annielennox.com |title=Ivor Novello Awards listed on official website |publisher=Annielennox.com |date=15 October 2010 |accessdate=27 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101206180756/http://www.annielennox.com/| archivedate= 6 December 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n*1984 \u2013 Songwriter of the Year for Lennox and Dave Stewart\n*1987 \u2013 Songwriter of the Year for Lennox and Dave Stewart\n*1987 \u2013 Best contemporary song (\"Its Alright, (Baby's Coming Back)\")\n*1993 \u2013 Best Song (\"Why\")\n\n; [[Honorary degrees]] and awards<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annielennox.com |title=Honorary degrees/ Awards listed on official website |publisher=Annielennox.com |date=15 October 2010 |accessdate=27 October 2010| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20101206180756/http://www.annielennox.com/| archivedate= 6 December 2010 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n*1986 \u2013 Associate \u2013 [[Royal Academy of Music]] London\n*1997 \u2013 Fellowship \u2013 [[Royal Academy of Music]] London\n*2006 \u2013 Honorary Doctor of Music \u2013 The [[Royal Scottish Academy of Music and Drama]]\n*2006 \u2013 Fellowship \u2013 [[Edinburgh College of Art]]\n*2009 \u2013 Honorary Doctorate at the [[University of Edinburgh]] (awarded 20 October 2009), in recognition of her work in the field of HIV/AIDS, and her success as a recording artist.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ed.ac.uk/news/all-news/lennox-201009 |title=Annie Lennox receives honorary degree &#124; News and events |publisher=Ed.ac.uk |date=22 October 2009 |accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref>\n*2011 \u2013 Honoured by the University for her International Humanitarian Efforts \u2013 [[Glasgow Caledonian University]]  \n*2012 \u2013 Honorary Degree  \u2013 [[Open University]] of Scotland\n*2013 \u2013 Honorary Degree \u2013 [[Williams College]] \n*2013 \u2013 Honorary Doctorate in Music \u2013 [[Berklee College of Music]] \n*2013 \u2013 Honorary Degree \u2013 [[University of Essex]]\n\n; Other awards/titles/ambassadorships<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.annielennox.com |title=Other awards/titles/ambassadorships listed on official website |publisher=Annielennox.com |date=15 October 2010 |accessdate=27 October 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101206180756/http://www.annielennox.com/ |archivedate=6 December 2010 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*2002 \u2013 [[Billboard Century Award]] by ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard'']]\n*2008 \u2013 OUT magazine honoured Lennox for her work in the HIV and AIDS field. The top 100 most influential people in Gay Culture.\n*2008 \u2013 The British Red Cross Services to Humanity Award\n*2008 \u2013 Glamour Magazine's Inspirational Woman of the Year Award\n*2008 \u2013 Honoured at the 2008 Youth AIDS Gala, for her contribution in helping the fight against HIV and AIDS\n*2008 \u2013 The German Sustainability \"special achievement\" award for her commitment in the fight against HIV and AIDS\n*2008 \u2013 [[Webby Award]] for official website www.annielennox.com<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Iuj6Lt1lbLc |title=Lennox's acceptance speech video on Youtube |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=27 October 2010}}</ref>\n*2009 \u2013 [[Save the Children]] \"Amigo de los Ni\u00f1os\" Award\n*2009 \u2013 Awarded the \"[[Freedom of the City of London]]\" by the British Red Cross for services to humanity in the field of HIV and AIDS\n*2009 \u2013 Nobel Peace Laureates for services to humanity\n*2010 \u2013 Patron of the [[Elton John AIDS Foundation]]\n*2010 \u2013 Special Envoy for HIV/AIDS in Scotland\n*2010 \u2013 Ambassador for HIV/AIDS in London\n*2010 \u2013 [[UNAIDS]] Goodwill Ambassador\n*2010 \u2013 [[Barclays]] Women of the Year Award\n*2010 \u2013 International Service Award for Global Defence of Human Rights<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internationalservice.org.uk/what_we_do/development_awareness/human_rights_awards/2010_awards/annie_lennox.aspx|title=International Service \u2013 annie lennox|publisher=Internationservice.org.uk|accessdate=27 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140911165632/http://www.internationalservice.org.uk/what_we_do/development_awareness/human_rights_awards/2010_awards/annie_lennox.aspx|archivedate=11 September 2014}}</ref>\n*2010 \u2013 [[GQ]] Charity Woman of the Year Award\n*2010 \u2013 Harper's Bazaar Lifetime Achievement Award\n*2010 \u2013 Appointed an [[Order of the British Empire|Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) for her work fighting AIDS and poverty in Africa\n*2013 \u2013 Music Industry Trust Award (MITS) for her creativity and work that inspires those who work within the music business and millions of others worldwide\n*2016 \u2013 [[Elle Style Awards]] \u2013 Outstanding Achievement Award\n*2016 \u2013 Awarded [[Livingstone Medal]] by [[Royal Scottish Geographical Society]] \n*2016 \u2013 Harper's Bazaar Philanthropy Award\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Annie Lennox}}\n{{Sister project links |commons=Annie Lennox}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.annielennox.com}}\n* {{AllMusic|id=annie-lennox-mn0000585249|name=Annie Lennox}}\n* [https://worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n92080019/ Annie Lennox] in libraries ([[WorldCat]] catalogue)\n* {{IMDb n